es of usability for people with disabilities</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For design o=
f products or environments for access by all users, see <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_design" title=3D"Universal design">Universa=
l design</a>. For design of websites etc. for access by all users, see <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_accessibility" title=3D"Web access=
ibility">Web accessibility</a>. For measures of spatial accessibility, see =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility_(transport)" title=
=3D"Accessibility (transport)">Accessibility (transport)</a>. For the logic=
al notion, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility_relat=
ion" title=3D"Accessibility relation">Accessibility relation</a>. For the p=
rocess in agenda-setting theory, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Agenda-setting_theory#Accessibility" title=3D"Agenda-setting theory">Age=
nda-setting theory =C2=A7&nbsp;Accessibility</a>.</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable s=
elfref">For Wikipedia's accessibility guideline, see <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Accessibility" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Wikipedia:Accessibility">Wikipedia:Accessibility</a>.</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:MAD_BS_Moon_fixtures_(cropped_2).jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"Panel on an elevator showing the floor=
 buttons with Braille markings" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/6/6b/MAD_BS_Moon_fixtures_%28cropped_2%29.jpg/250px-MAD_BS=
_Moon_fixtures_%28cropped_2%29.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"189" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2245" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"1698"></a><figcaption>Elevator buttons with Braille markings</figcapti=
on></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Curitiba_10_2006_05_RIT.jpg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img alt=3D"A woman with a baby carriage uses a platform lift=
 to access a station above street level" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1e/Curitiba_10_2006_05_RIT.jpg/250px-Curitiba_1=
0_2006_05_RIT.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"214" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1772" data-file-height=3D"1518"></a><f=
igcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rede_Integrada_de_Tr=
ansporte" title=3D"Rede Integrada de Transporte">public transport system in=
 Curitiba</a>, Brazil, offers universal access via <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Wheelchair_lift" title=3D"Wheelchair lift">wheelchair lift=
s</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Accessibility</b> is the design of products, devices, services, vehic=
les, or environments to be usable by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Disabled" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Disabled">disabled</a> people.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The concept of accessible des=
ign and practice of accessible developments ensures both "direct access" (i=
.e. unassisted) and "indirect access" meaning compatibility with a person's=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assistive_technology" title=3D"As=
sistive technology">assistive technology</a> (for example, computer <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Screen_reader" title=3D"Screen reader">sc=
reen readers</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Accessibility can be viewed as the "ability to access" and benefit f=
rom some system or entity. The concept focuses on enabling access for peopl=
e with disabilities, or enabling access through the use of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assistive_technology" title=3D"Assistive technolog=
y">assistive technology</a>; however, research and development in accessibi=
lity brings benefits to everyone.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-3"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#ci=
te_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Accessibility#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Therefore, an accessible society sh=
ould eliminate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_divide" tit=
le=3D"Digital divide">digital divide</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Knowledge_divide" title=3D"Knowledge divide">knowledge divide</a>=
.
</p><p>Accessibility is not to be confused with <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Usability" title=3D"Usability">usability</a>, which is the ex=
tent to which a product (such as a device, service, or environment) can be =
used by specified users to achieve specified goals with effectiveness, effi=
ciency, and satisfaction in a specified context of use.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibili=
ty#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Accessibility is also strongly related to <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Universal_design" title=3D"Universal design">universal desig=
n</a>, the process of creating products that are usable by the widest possi=
ble range of people, operating within the widest possible range of situatio=
ns.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Universal design typicall=
y provides a single general solution that can accommodate people with disab=
ilities as well as the rest of the population. By contrast, accessible desi=
gn is focused on ensuring that there are no barriers to accessibility for a=
ll people, including those with disabilities.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Legislation">Legislation</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Legislation"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:MUTCD_D9-6.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img alt=3D"White line figure of a person seated over the axis of a wheel =
on blue background" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t=
humb/f/f2/MUTCD_D9-6.svg/250px-MUTCD_D9-6.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2880" =
data-file-height=3D"2880"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/International_Symbol_of_Access" title=3D"International Symbol of Ac=
cess">International Symbol of Access</a> denotes area with access for those=
 with disabilities.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disability_rights_movement"=
 title=3D"Disability rights movement">disability rights movement</a> advoca=
tes equal access to social, political, and economic life which includes not=
 only physical access but access to the same tools, services, organizations=
 and facilities as non-disabled people (e.g., museums<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibilit=
y#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-11"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>). Article 9 of the United Nations <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Convention_on_the_Rights_of_Persons_with_Disabilities" title=3D"Conventio=
n on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities">Convention on the Rights of P=
ersons with Disabilities</a> commits signatories to provide for full access=
ibility in their countries.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-12"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>While it is often used to describe facilities or amenities to assist=
 people with impaired mobility, through the provision of facilities like <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wheelchair_ramp" title=3D"Wheelchair=
 ramp">wheelchair ramps</a>, the term can include other types of disability=
. Accessible facilities therefore extend to areas such as <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Braille" title=3D"Braille">Braille</a> signage, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elevator" title=3D"Elevator">elevator=
s</a>, audio signals at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedestrian=
_crossing" title=3D"Pedestrian crossing">pedestrian crossings</a>, walkway =
contours, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Website_accessibility" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Website accessibility">website accessibility<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessible_publishing" tit=
le=3D"Accessible publishing">accessible publishing</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibil=
ity#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the United States, government mandates including Section 508, WCA=
G,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> DDA are all enforcing p=
ractices to standardize accessibility testing engineering in product develo=
pment.
</p><p>Accessibility modifications may be required to enable persons with d=
isabilities to gain access to education, employment, transportation, housin=
g, recreation, or even simply to exercise their right to vote.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"National_legislation">Natio=
nal legislation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section:=
 National legislation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Various countries have legislation requiring physical accessibility whic=
h are (in order of enactment):
</p>
<ul><li>In the US, under the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ameri=
cans_with_Disabilities_Act_of_1990" title=3D"Americans with Disabilities Ac=
t of 1990">Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibil=
ity#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> new public and private business construction =
generally must be accessible. Existing private businesses are required to i=
ncrease the accessibility of their facilities when making any other renovat=
ions in proportion to the cost of the other renovations. The <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Access_Board" title=3D"United Stat=
es Access Board">United States Access Board</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite=
_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> is "A Federal Agency Committed to Accessible Design f=
or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Americans_with_disabilities" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Americans with disabilities">People with Disab=
ilities</a>". The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Job_Accommodatio=
n_Network" title=3D"Job Accommodation Network">Job Accommodation Network</a=
> discusses accommodations for people with disabilities in the workplace.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Many states in the US have =
their own disability laws.</li>
<li>In Australia, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disability_D=
iscrimination_Act_1992" title=3D"Disability Discrimination Act 1992">Disabi=
lity Discrimination Act 1992</a> has numerous provisions for accessibility.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>In South Africa the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Promotion_=
of_Equality_and_Prevention_of_Unfair_Discrimination_Act_2000" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Promotion of Equality and Prevention of Unfair Discrimina=
tion Act 2000">Promotion of Equality and Prevention of Unfair Discriminatio=
n Act 2000</a> has numerous provisions for accessibility.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessib=
ility#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>In the UK, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equality_Act_20=
10" title=3D"Equality Act 2010">Equality Act 2010</a> has numerous provisio=
ns for accessibility.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>In Sri Lanka, the Supreme Court, on 27 April 2011 gave a landmark order=
 to boost the inherent right of disabled persons to have unhindered access =
to public buildings and facilities.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-21"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup></li>
<li>In Norway, the Discrimination and Accessibility Act (<a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norwegian_language" title=3D"Norwegian language">Nor=
wegian</a>: <i lang=3D"no">Diskriminerings- og tilgjengelighetsloven</i>) d=
efines lack of accessibility as discrimination and obliges public authoriti=
es to implement universal design in their areas. The Act refers to issue-sp=
ecific legislation regarding accessibility in e.g. ICT, the built environme=
nt, transport and education.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-22"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p></li>
<li>In Brazil, the law on the inclusion of people with disabilities has num=
erous provisions for accessibility.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-23"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup></li>
<li>In Canada, relevant federal legislation includes the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_Human_Rights_Act" title=3D"Canadian Human R=
ights Act">Canadian Human Rights Act</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Employment_equity_(Canada)" title=3D"Employment equity (Canada)">th=
e Employment Equity Act</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
anadian_Labour_Code" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Canadian Labour Code">C=
anadian Labour Code</a>, and the Accessible Canada Act (Bill-C81) which mad=
e Royal Assent on June 21, 2019.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-24"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup></li></ul>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beach_accessibility_mobi-mat_and_wheelchair_r=
amp.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"Beachshore with a mobi-m=
at leading from the kerb to the seashore" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.o=
rg/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Beach_accessibility_mobi-mat_and_wheelchair=
_ramp.jpg/250px-Beach_accessibility_mobi-mat_and_wheelchair_ramp.jpg" decod=
ing=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-f=
ile-width=3D"4032" data-file-height=3D"3024"></a><figcaption>Ramps and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobi-mat" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Mobi-mat">mobi-mats</a> enable wheelchair users to visit a sandy seasho=
re.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Legislation may also be enacted on a state, provincial or local level. I=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ontario,_Canada" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Ontario, Canada">Ontario, Canada</a>, the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ontarians_with_Disabilities_Act" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Ontarians with Disabilities Act">Ontarians with Disabilities A=
ct</a> of 2001 is meant to "improve the identification, removal and prevent=
ion of barriers faced by persons with disabilities".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility=
#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Union" title=
=3D"European Union">European Union</a> (EU), which has signed the United Na=
tions' Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities, also has adop=
ted a European Disability Strategy for 2010=E2=80=9320. The Strategy includ=
es the following goals, among others:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-26">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Devising policies for inclusive, high-quality education;</li>
<li>Ensuring the European Platform Against Poverty includes a special focus=
 on people with disabilities (the forum brings together experts who share b=
est practices and experience);</li>
<li>Working towards the recognition of disability cards throughout the EU t=
o ensure equal treatment when working, living or travelling in the bloc</li=
>
<li>Establishing accessibility standards for voting locations and campaign =
materials.</li>
<li>Taking the rights of people with disabilities into account in external =
development programmes and for EU candidate countries.</li></ul>
<p>A <i>European Accessibility Act</i> was proposed in late 2012.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Accessibility#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This Act would establish standards =
within member countries for accessible products, services, and public build=
ings. The harmonization of accessibility standards within the EU "would fac=
ilitate the social integration of persons with disabilities and the elderly=
 and their mobility across member states, thereby also fostering the free m=
ovement principle".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Enforcement of the European Accessibility Act (EAA) begins in June 2=
025
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Assistive_technology_and_ad=
aptive_technology">Assistive technology and adaptive technology</h2><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Assistive technology and a=
daptive technology"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Birmingham_opportunities_fair.jpg" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img alt=3D"People gathered around a table wearing head=
phones. The journalist holds the microphone for a physically disabled perso=
n to speak" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4=
e/Birmingham_opportunities_fair.jpg/250px-Birmingham_opportunities_fair.jpg=
" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"166" class=3D"mw-file-element"=
 data-file-width=3D"4288" data-file-height=3D"2848"></a><figcaption>The Opp=
ortunities Fair and Beyond Art Exhibition was organised in <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birmingham" title=3D"Birmingham">Birmingham</a>, E=
ngland, to help people with disabilities and their carers find out what ser=
vices, support and opportunities are available to them.</figcaption></figur=
e>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assistive_technology" title=3D"=
Assistive technology">Assistive technology</a> is the creation of a new dev=
ice that assists a person in completing a task that would otherwise be impo=
ssible. Some examples include new computer software programs like <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Screen_reader" title=3D"Screen reader">sc=
reen readers</a>, and inventions such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Assistive_listening_devices" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Assistiv=
e listening devices">assistive listening devices</a>, including <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hearing_aid" title=3D"Hearing aid">hearing ai=
ds</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traffic_light" title=
=3D"Traffic light">traffic lights</a> with a standard <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color_code" title=3D"Color code">color code</a> that en=
ables <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colorblind" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Colorblind">colorblind</a> individuals to understand the cor=
rect signal.
</p><p>Adaptive technology is the modification, or adaptation, of existing =
devices, methods, or the creation of new uses for existing devices, to enab=
le a person to complete a task.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-29"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Examples include the use of remote controls, and the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autocomplete" title=3D"Autocomplete">autocomplete<=
/a> (word completion)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> feat=
ure in computer word processing programs, which both help individuals with =
mobility impairments to complete tasks. Adaptations to wheelchair tires are=
 another example; widening the tires enables wheelchair users to move over =
soft surfaces, such as deep snow on ski hills, and sandy beaches.
</p><p>Assistive technology and adaptive technology have a key role in deve=
loping the means for people with disabilities to live more independently, a=
nd to more fully participate in mainstream society. Recent research has dem=
onstrated that tablet-based assistive technologies can enable adults with i=
ntellectual and motor disabilities to engage in independent leisure activit=
ies and video communication, enhancing social participation and autonomy. T=
hese programs use commercially available tablets and applications with simp=
lified interfaces to support users in accessing media and making video call=
s with minimal assistance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-31"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
In order to have access to assistive or adaptive technology, however, educa=
ting the public and even legislating requirements to incorporate this techn=
ology have been necessary.
</p><p>The UN CRPD, and courts in the United States, Japan, UK, and elsewhe=
re, have decided that when it is needed to assure secret ballot, authoritie=
s should provide voters with assistive technology.
</p><p>The European Court of Human Rights, on the contrary, in case Toplak =
v. Slovenia ruled that due to high costs, the abandonment of the assistive =
equipment in elections did not violate human rights.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Employment">Employment</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Employment"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Usda_hiring_applicants_with_disabilities.jpg"=
 class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A man is speaking behind a micro=
phone podium during a conference. Behind him, there is a screen showing a p=
resentation slide reading &quot;Four Simple Steps to Hiring Qualified Candi=
dates with Disabilities&quot;" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedi=
a/commons/thumb/c/c9/Usda_hiring_applicants_with_disabilities.jpg/250px-Usd=
a_hiring_applicants_with_disabilities.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250"=
 height=3D"350" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1500" data-fil=
e-height=3D"2100"></a><figcaption>William P. Milton Jr., deputy director of=
 the Office of Human Resource Management, outlined the "Four Simple Steps t=
o Hiring Qualified Candidates with Disabilities" to employees of the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Department_of_Agriculture"=
 title=3D"United States Department of Agriculture">U.S. Department of Agric=
ulture</a> during a 2011 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_=
Disability_Employment_Awareness_Month" title=3D"National Disability Employm=
ent Awareness Month">National Disability Employment Awareness Month</a> eve=
nt in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington,_D.C." title=3D"W=
ashington, D.C.">Washington, D.C.</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>Accessibility of employment covers a wide range of issues, from skills t=
raining, to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occupational_therapy" =
title=3D"Occupational therapy">occupational therapy</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibi=
lity#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> finding employment, and retaining employment=
.
</p><p>Employment rates for workers with disabilities are lower than for th=
e general workforce. Workers in Western countries fare relatively well, hav=
ing access to more services and training as well as legal protections again=
st employment discrimination. Despite this, in the United States the 2012 u=
nemployment rate for workers with disabilities was 12.9%, while it was 7.3%=
 for workers without disabilities.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-33"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> More than half of workers with disabilities (52%) earned less than=
 $25,000 in the previous year, compared with just 38% of workers with no di=
sabilities. This translates into an earnings gap where individuals with dis=
abilities earn about 25 percent less of what workers without disabilities e=
arn. Among occupations with 100,000 or more people, dishwashers had the hig=
hest disability rate (14.3%), followed by refuse and recyclable material co=
llectors (12.7%), personal care aides (11.9%), and janitors and building cl=
eaners (11.8%). The rates for refuse and recyclable material collectors, pe=
rsonal care aides, and janitors and building cleaners were not statisticall=
y different from one another.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-34"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>Surveys of non-Western countries are limited, but the available stat=
istics also indicate fewer jobs being filled by workers with disabilities. =
In India, a large 1999 survey found that "of the 'top 100 multinational com=
panies' in the country [...] the employment rate of persons with disabiliti=
es in the private sector was a mere 0.28%, 0.05% in multinational companies=
 and only 0.58% in the top 100 IT companies in the country".<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-dsq-sds_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-dsq-sds-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> India, like much of th=
e world, has large sections of the economy that are without strong regulati=
on or social protections, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Informal_economy" title=3D"Informal economy">informal economy</a>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other factors have been cited =
as contributing to the high unemployment rate, such as public service regul=
ations. Although employment for workers with disabilities is higher in the =
public sector due to hiring programs targeting persons with disabilities, r=
egulations currently restrict types of work available to persons with disab=
ilities:
"Disability-specific employment reservations are limited to the public sect=
or and a large number of the reserved positions continue to be vacant despi=
te nearly two decades of enactment of the PWD Act".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dsq-=
sds_35-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acce=
ssibility#cite_note-dsq-sds-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Expenses related to adaptive or assistive technology required to par=
ticipate in the workforce may be tax deductible expenses for individuals wi=
th a medical practitioner's prescription in some jurisdictions.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Disability_management">Disa=
bility management</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Disability management"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Disability management (DM) is a specialized area of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_resources" title=3D"Human resources">human resou=
rces</a> that supports efforts of employers to better integrate and retain =
workers with disabilities. Some workplaces have policies in place to provid=
e "reasonable accommodation" for employees with disabilities, but many do n=
ot. In some jurisdictions, employers may have legal requirements to end <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ableism" title=3D"Ableism">discrimina=
tion against persons with disabilities</a>.
</p><p>It has been noted by researchers that where accommodations are in pl=
ace for employees with disabilities, these frequently apply to individuals =
with "pre-determined or apparent disabilities as determined by national soc=
ial protection or Equality Authorities",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Geisen165_37-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility=
#cite_note-Geisen165-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which include persons with pre-existin=
g conditions who receive an official disability designation. One of the big=
gest challenges for employers is in developing policies and practises to ma=
nage employees who develop disabilities during the course of employment. Ev=
en where these exist, they tend to focus on workplace injuries, overlooking=
 job retention challenges faced by employees who acquire a non-occupation i=
njury or illness. Protecting employability is a factor that can help close =
the unemployment gap for persons with disabilities.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Geis=
en165_37-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ac=
cessibility#cite_note-Geisen165-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Transportation">Transportat=
ion</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessib=
ility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Transportat=
ion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
For the metric of transport connectivity for planning purposes, see <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility_(transport)" title=3D"Acces=
sibility (transport)">Accessibility (transport)</a>.</div>
<p>Providing mobility to people with disabilities includes changes for publ=
ic facilities like gently sloping paths of travel for people using wheelcha=
irs and difficulty walking up stairs, or audio announcements for the blind =
(either live or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAut=
omated_on-train_announcements&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"n=
ew" title=3D"Automated on-train announcements (page does not exist)">automa=
ted</a>); dedicated services like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Paratransit" title=3D"Paratransit">paratransit</a>; and adaptations to pers=
onal vehicles.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Adapted_automobiles_for_per=
sons_with_disabilities">Adapted automobiles for persons with disabilities</=
h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[<=
/span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Adapted automobi=
les for persons with disabilities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adapted_automobile" titl=
e=3D"Adapted automobile">Adapted automobile</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Taxi_wheelchair.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96=
/Taxi_wheelchair.jpg/250px-Taxi_wheelchair.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3648" dat=
a-file-height=3D"2736"></a><figcaption>A wheelchair accessible <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxi" title=3D"Taxi">taxi</a> with a rear ramp=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tokyo_Motor_Show" title=3D"Tokyo=
 Motor Show">Tokyo Motor Show</a> 2009</figcaption></figure>
<p>Automobile accessibility also refers to ease of use by disabled people. =
Automobiles, whether a car or a van, can be adapted for a range of physical=
 disabilities. Foot pedals can be raised, or replaced with hand-controlled =
devices. Wheelchair hoists, lifts or ramps may be customized according to t=
he needs of the driver. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ergonomic"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ergonomic">Ergonomic</a> adaptations, such =
as a lumbar support cushion, may also be needed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cit=
e_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Generally, the more limiting the disability, the more expensive the =
adaptation needed for the vehicle. Financial assistance is available throug=
h some organizations, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mota=
bility" title=3D"Motability">Motability</a> in the United Kingdom, which re=
quires a contribution by the prospective vehicle owner. Motability makes ve=
hicles available for purchase or lease.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-39=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>When an employee with a disability requires an adapted car for work =
use, the employee does not have to pay for a "<a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Reasonable_accommodation" title=3D"Reasonable accommodation">re=
asonable adjustment</a>" in the United Kingdom; if the employer is unable t=
o pay the cost, assistance is offered by government programs.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acce=
ssibility#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Low_floor">Low floor</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Low floor"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
"Low floor" redirects here. For more details, see <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Low-floor_bus" title=3D"Low-floor bus">Low-floor bus</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low-floor_tram" title=3D"Low-flo=
or tram">Low-floor tram</a>.</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Person_on_PMD_boarding_an_SMRT_bus,_August_20=
22.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A man on a motorized whee=
lchair is using a ramp to enter an SMRT bus" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedi=
a.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Person_on_PMD_boarding_an_SMRT_bus%2C_Au=
gust_2022.jpg/250px-Person_on_PMD_boarding_an_SMRT_bus%2C_August_2022.jpg" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"179" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"3415" data-file-height=3D"2439"></a><figcaption>Wheelchai=
r ramps allows those on wheelchairs or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Personal_transporter" title=3D"Personal transporter">personal mobility=
 devices</a> to board low-floor public transport vehicles.</figcaption></fi=
gure>
<p>A significant development in transportation, and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Public_transport" title=3D"Public transport">public trans=
port</a> in particular, to achieve accessibility, is the move to "low-floor=
" vehicles. In a low-floor vehicle, access to part or all of the passenger =
cabin is unobstructed from one or more entrances by the presence of steps, =
enabling easier access for the infirm or people with <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Baby_transport" title=3D"Baby transport">push chairs</a>=
. A further aspect may be that the entrance and corridors are wide enough t=
o accommodate a wheelchair. Low-floor vehicles have been developed for <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bus" title=3D"Bus">buses</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trolleybus" title=3D"Trolleybus">trolleyb=
uses</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trams" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Trams">trams</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Train" title=3D"Train">trains</a>.
</p><p>A low floor in the vehicular sense is normally combined in a concept=
ual meaning with normal pedestrian access from a standard <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curb" title=3D"Curb">kerb (curb)</a> height. Howeve=
r, the accessibility of a low-floor vehicle can also be utilised from sligh=
tly raising portions of kerb at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bu=
s_stop" title=3D"Bus stop">bus stops</a>, or through use of level boarding =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bus_rapid_transit" title=3D"Bus ra=
pid transit">bus rapid transit</a> stations or tram stops.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessi=
bility#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The combination of access from a kerb was =
the technological development of the 1990s, as step-free interior layouts f=
or buses had existed in some cases for decades, with entrance steps being i=
ntroduced as chassis designs and overall height regulations changed.
</p><p>Low-floor buses may also be designed with special height adjustment =
controls that permit a stationary bus to temporarily lower itself to ground=
 level, permitting wheelchair access. This is referred to as a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kneeling_bus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"K=
neeling bus">kneeling bus</a>.
</p><p>At <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rapid_transit" title=3D"=
Rapid transit">rapid transit</a> systems, vehicles generally have floors in=
 the same height as the platforms but the stations are often underground or=
 elevated, so accessibility there is not a question of providing low-floor =
vehicles, but providing a step-free access from street level to the platfor=
ms (generally by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elevator" title=
=3D"Elevator">elevators</a>, which may be restricted to disabled passengers=
 only, so that the step-free access is not obstructed by non-disabled peopl=
e taking advantage).<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" st=
yle=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wi=
kipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D=
"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2022)">citation need=
ed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Accessibility_planning_for_=
transportation_in_the_United_Kingdom">Accessibility planning for transporta=
tion in the United Kingdom</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"=
Edit section: Accessibility planning for transportation in the United Kingd=
om"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Harrington_railway_station,_Cumbria_(geograph=
_3564245).jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wik=
imedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4d/Harrington_railway_station%2C_Cumbr=
ia_%28geograph_3564245%29.jpg/250px-Harrington_railway_station%2C_Cumbria_%=
28geograph_3564245%29.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" =
class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1024" data-file-height=3D"768"=
></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harrington_Hump" =
title=3D"Harrington Hump">Harrington Hump</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Harrington_station" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Harrington =
station">Harrington station</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" title=3D=
"United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>, local transport authorities are respon=
sible for checking that all people who live within their area can access es=
sential opportunities and services, and where gaps in provision are identif=
ied the local authorities are responsible for organizing changes to make ne=
w connections. These requirements are defined in the UK Community Planning =
Acts legislation<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and more =
detailed guidance has been issued by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Department_for_Transport" title=3D"Department for Transport">Departm=
ent for Transport</a> for each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loc=
al_authority#England" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Local authority">local=
 authority</a>. This includes the requirement to produce an Accessibility P=
lan under Community Planning legislation and to incorporate this within the=
ir <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_Transport_Plan" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Local Transport Plan">Local Transport Plan</a>.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Accessibility#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An Accessibility Plan sets out =
how each local authority plans to improve access to employment, learning, h=
ealth care, food shops and other services of local importance, particularly=
 for disadvantaged groups and areas. Accessibility targets are defined in t=
he accessibility plans, these are often the distance or time to access serv=
ices by different modes of transport including walking, cycling and public =
transport.
</p><p>Accessibility Planning was introduced as a result of the report "Mak=
ing the Connections: Final Report on Transport and Social Exclusion".<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Accessibility#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This report was the result of r=
esearch carried out by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_=
exclusion" title=3D"Social exclusion">Social Exclusion</a> Unit. The United=
 Kingdom also has a "code of practice" for making train and stations access=
ible: "Accessible Train and Station Design for Disabled People: A Code of P=
ractice".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This code of pra=
ctice was first published in 2002 with the objective of compliance to Secti=
on 71B of the Railways Act 1993,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-46"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> and revised after a public consultation period in 2008.
</p><p>Some transport companies have since improved the accessibility of th=
eir services, such as incorporating <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Low-floor_bus" title=3D"Low-floor bus">low-floor buses</a> into their sto=
ck as standard.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"Th=
is claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2021)">citation need=
ed</span></a></i>]</sup> In August 2021, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/South_Western_Railway_(train_operating_company)" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"South Western Railway (train operating company)">South Western =
Railway</a> announced the streamlining of their accessibility services, all=
owing passengers requiring assistance to inform the company with as little =
as 10 minutes' notice at all 189 stations on its network, replacing an olde=
r scheme wherein assisted journeys had to be booked six hours to a day in a=
dvance. The system will utilise clear signage at stations and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/QR_code" title=3D"QR code">QR codes</a>, allowi=
ng customers to send details of the assistance they require and their plann=
ed journey to staff remotely.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-47"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>Making public services fully accessible to the public has led to som=
e technological innovations. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Publi=
c_announcement" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Public announcement">Public =
announcement</a> systems using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aud=
io_induction_loop" title=3D"Audio induction loop">audio induction loop</a> =
technology can broadcast announcements directly into the hearing aid of any=
one with a hearing impairment, making them useful in such public places as =
auditoriums and train stations.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Public_space">Public space<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibilit=
y&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Public space">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convention_on_the_Rights_of=
_Persons_with_Disabilities" title=3D"Convention on the Rights of Persons wi=
th Disabilities">UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities</=
a> (2006) requires 'appropriate measures' to ensure people with disabilitie=
s are able to 'access, on an equal basis with others','the physical environ=
ment', 'transportation' and 'other facilities and services open or provided=
 to the public'. This requirement also applies to 'roads' and 'transportati=
on' as well as 'buildings, and other indoor and outdoor facilities'.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Accessibility#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>At the same time, promotion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Active_mobility" title=3D"Active mobility">active travel</a>, or 'share=
d space' initiatives to pedestrianise city centres can introduce unintended=
 barriers, especially for pedestrians who are visually impaired and who can=
 find these environments confusing or even dangerous.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0=
_49-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessi=
bility#cite_note-:0-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is important to have effective mech=
anisms to ensure that urban spaces are designed to be inclusive of pedestri=
ans with disabilities. These can include early consultation with disabled p=
ersons or their representative organisations, and appropriate regulation of=
 city planning.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_49-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-:0-49"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Housing">Housing</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Housing"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessible_ho=
using" title=3D"Accessible housing">Accessible housing</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:-118wiki.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><=
img alt=3D"An entrance with ramps and guardrails" src=3D"https://upload.wik=
imedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/-118wiki.jpg/250px--118wiki.jpg" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"314" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"6645" data-file-height=3D"8352"></a><figcaption>Accessibly =
designed modification for a high-step entrance</figcaption></figure>
<p>Most existing and new housing, even in the wealthiest nations, lack basi=
c accessibility features unless the designated, immediate occupant of a hom=
e currently has a disability. However, there are some initiatives to change=
 typical residential practices so that new homes incorporate basic access f=
eatures such as zero-step entries and door widths adequate for wheelchairs =
to pass through. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occupational_Ther=
apist" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Occupational Therapist">Occupational =
Therapists</a> are a professional group skilled in the assessment and makin=
g of recommendations to improve access to homes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cit=
e_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> They are involved in both the adaptation of existing=
 housing to improve accessibility,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-51"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> and in the design of future housing.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_=
note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The broad concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Univer=
sal_design" title=3D"Universal design">Universal design</a> is relevant to =
housing, as it is to all aspects of the built environment. Furthermore, a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visitability" title=3D"Visitability=
">Visitability</a> movement<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-53"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> begun by grass roots disability advocates in the 1980s focuses specifical=
ly on changing construction practices in new housing. This movement, a netw=
ork of interested people working in their locales, works on educating, pass=
ing laws, and spurring voluntary home access initiatives with the intention=
 that basic access become a routine part of new home construction.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Accessibility_and_&quot;age=
ing_in_place&quot;"><span id=3D"Accessibility_and_.22ageing_in_place.22"></=
span>Accessibility and "ageing in place"</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
12" title=3D"Edit section: Accessibility and &quot;ageing in place&quot;"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>Accessibility in the design of housing and household devices has become =
more prominent in recent decades due to a rapidly ageing population in deve=
loped countries.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Ageing se=
niors may wish to continue living independently, but the ageing process nat=
urally increases the disabilities that a senior citizen will experience. A =
growing trend is the desire for many senior citizens to 'age in place', liv=
ing as independently as possible for as long as possible. Accessibility mod=
ifications that allow ageing in place are becoming more common. Housing may=
 even be designed to incorporate accessibility modifications that can be ma=
de throughout the life cycle of the residents.
</p><p>The English Housing Survey for 2018/19 found only 9% of homes in Eng=
land have key features, such as a toilet at entrance level and sufficiently=
 wide doorways, to deem them accessible. This was an improvement from 5% in=
 2005. More than 400,000 wheelchair users in England were living in homes w=
hich are neither adapted nor accessible.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-5=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Voting">Voting</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Voting"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Under the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convention_on_the_Rig=
hts_of_Persons_with_Disabilities" title=3D"Convention on the Rights of Pers=
ons with Disabilities">Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilitie=
s</a>, states parties are bound to assure accessible <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Election" title=3D"Election">elections</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voting" title=3D"Voting">voting</a>, and votin=
g procedures. In 2018, the United Nations <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Committee_on_the_Rights_of_Persons_with_Disabilities" title=3D"Comm=
ittee on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities">Committee on the Rights o=
f Persons with Disabilities</a> issued an opinion that all polling stations=
 should be fully accessible. At the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/European_Court_of_Human_Rights" title=3D"European Court of Human Rights">=
European Court of Human Rights</a>, there are currently two ongoing cases a=
bout the accessibility of polling places and voting procedures. They were b=
rought against <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slovenia" title=3D"=
Slovenia">Slovenia</a> by two voters and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Slovenian_Disability_Rights_Association" title=3D"Slovenian Disa=
bility Rights Association">Slovenian Disability Rights Association</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As of January 2020, the case,=
 called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toplak_and_Mrak_v._Sloveni=
a" title=3D"Toplak and Mrak v. Slovenia">Toplak and Mrak v. Slovenia</a>, w=
as ongoing.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-57" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The aim of the=
 court procedure is to make accessible all polling places in Europe.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Accessibility#cite_note-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Disability,_information_tec=
hnology_(IT)_and_telecommunications"><span id=3D"Disability.2C_information_=
technology_.28IT.29_and_telecommunications"></span>Disability, information =
technology (IT) and telecommunications</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14=
" title=3D"Edit section: Disability, information technology (IT) and teleco=
mmunications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
