<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Mobility_impairments">Mobil=
ity impairments</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section=
: Mobility impairments"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>One of the first areas where information technology improved the quality=
 of life for disabled individuals is the voice operated wheelchair. Quadrip=
legics have the most profound disability, and the voice operated wheelchair=
 technology was first developed in 1977 to provide increased mobility. The =
original version replaced the joystick system with a module that recognized=
 8 commands. Many other technology accommodation improvements have evolved =
from this initial development.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-67"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>Missing arms or fingers may make the use of a keyboard and mouse dif=
ficult or impossible. Technological improvements such as <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speech_recognition" title=3D"Speech recognition">spe=
ech recognition</a> devices and software can improve access.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Communication_(including_sp=
eech)_impairments"><span id=3D"Communication_.28including_speech.29_impairm=
ents"></span>Communication (including speech) impairments</h4><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Communication (including s=
peech) impairments"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A communication disorder interferes with the ability to produce clearly =
understandable speech. There can be many different causes, such as nerve de=
generation, muscle degeneration, stroke, and vocal cord injury. The modern =
method to deal with speaking disabilities has been to provide a text interf=
ace for a speech synthesizer for complete vocal disability. This can be a g=
reat improvement for people that have been limited to the use of a throat v=
ibrator to produce speech since the 1960s.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Hearing_impairment">Hearing=
 impairment</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Accessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: He=
aring impairment"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>An individual satisfies the definition of hearing disabled when hearing =
loss is about 30&nbsp;dB for a single frequency, but this is not always per=
ceptible as a disability.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-68"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 For example, loss of sensitivity in one ear interferes with <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sound_localization" title=3D"Sound localization"=
>sound localization</a> (directional hearing), which can interfere with com=
munication in a crowd. This is often recognized when certain words are conf=
used during normal conversation. This can interfere with voice-only interfa=
ces, like automated customer service telephone systems, because it is somet=
imes difficult to increase the volume and repeat the message.
</p><p>Mild to moderate hearing loss may be accommodated with a hearing aid=
 that amplifies ambient sounds. Portable devices with speed recognition tha=
t can produce text can reduce problems associated with understanding conver=
sation. This kind of hearing loss is relatively common, and this often grow=
s worse with age.
</p><p>The modern method to deal with profound hearing disability is the In=
ternet using email or word processing applications. The <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telecommunications_device_for_the_deaf" title=3D"Tele=
communications device for the deaf">telecommunications device for the deaf<=
/a> (TDD) became available in the form of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Teleprinter" title=3D"Teleprinter">teletype</a> (TTY) during th=
e 1960s. These devices consist of a keyboard, display and modem that connec=
ts two or more of these devices using a dedicated wire or plain old telepho=
ne service.
</p><p>Modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_animation" =
title=3D"Computer animation">computer animation</a> allows for <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sign_language" title=3D"Sign language">sign la=
nguage</a> avatars to be integrated into public areas. This technology coul=
d potentially make train station announcements, news broadcasts, etc. acces=
sible when a human interpreter is not available.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cit=
e_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-70"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Sign language can also be incorporated into film; for example, all movies =
shown in Brazilian movie theaters must have a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Brazilian_Sign_Language" title=3D"Brazilian Sign Language">Braz=
ilian Sign Language</a> video track available to play alongside the film vi=
a a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_screen" title=3D"Second=
 screen">second screen</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-71"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-72" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>72<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Visual_impairments">Visual =
impairments</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Accessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Vi=
sual impairments"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>A wide array of technology products is available to assist with visual i=
mpairment. These include screen magnification for monitors, screen-reading =
software for computers and mobile devices, mouse-over speech synthesis for =
browsing, braille displays, braille printers, braille cameras, and voice-ac=
tivated phones and tablets.
</p><p>One emerging product that will make ordinary computer displays avail=
able for the blind is the refreshable tactile display, which is very differ=
ent from a conventional braille display. This provides a raised surface cor=
responding to the bright and dim spots on a conventional display. An exampl=
e is the Touch Sight Camera for the Blind.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speech_Synthesis_Markup_Lan=
guage" title=3D"Speech Synthesis Markup Language">Speech Synthesis Markup L=
anguage</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speech_Recognition_Grammar_Specification" ti=
tle=3D"Speech Recognition Grammar Specification">Speech Recognition Grammar=
 Specification</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-74" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>) are re=
latively recent technologies intended to standardize communication interfac=
es using Augmented <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backus%E2%80%93=
Naur_form" title=3D"Backus=E2=80=93Naur form">BNF</a> Form and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XML" title=3D"XML">XML</a> Form. These technol=
ogies assist visual impairments and physical impairment by providing intera=
ctive access to web content without the need to visually observe the conten=
t. While these technologies provides access for visually impaired individua=
ls, the primary benefactor has been automated systems that replace live hum=
an customer service representatives that handle telephone calls.
{Short description|Design guidelines for developing applications}}
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Cognitive_impairments">Cogn=
itive impairments</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Cognitive impairments"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><b>Cognitive accessibility</b> refers to a system or application being s=
uitable for use by individuals with developmental disabilities (DD)<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-75" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Accessibility#cite_note-75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>or intellectual disabilities  (ID=
).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Generally, this also in=
cludes neurotypical users.  Systems specifically designed for users with ID=
 are often referred to as adapted (aka assistive technology), and such syst=
ems may not be helpful for neurotypical persons.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-77" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cit=
e_note-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Systems that are usable for persons with ID are ofte=
n referred to as adaptable. Adapted systems may include simplified interfac=
es and internal logic. One such system is the '<a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Simple_Wikipedia" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Simple Wikipe=
dia">Simple Wikipedia</a>.' A system that is adaptable may include travel t=
icket dispensers and user interfaces with dual modes (standard and expert).=
 Design for cognitive accessibility is often bounded by defining users with=
 abilities above certain levels.
</p><p>Most of the supporting work for design for cognitive accessibility i=
s for adapted systems, a subset of assistive technology. There have been so=
me attempts to support adaptable systems,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-78" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-=
78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> but not much progress has been made
</p><p>Problem framing: One of the most daunting problems with any sort of =
project involving access by cognitively disabled persons is understanding t=
he end users. Also, in many instances, systems for this group of end-users =
also involve a secondary group of caregivers. Both groups need to have thei=
r needs and wants carefully considered.
</p><p>Standards There are several frameworks and standards to guide develo=
pers for adapted systems. Most notable are the ISO group and Resna. Example=
s of these standards: RESNA - ANSI/RESNA CA-1:2016<sup id=3D"cite_ref-79" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#c=
ite_note-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>79<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> ISO - ISO-TC173-WG10_N238_ISO 21801-1 2020<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-80" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Accessibility#cite_note-80"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>As well as parts of the World Wid=
e Web Consortium's WAI-IG,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-81"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 and WebAIM's Cognitive accessibility design considerations.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-82" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acces=
sibility#cite_note-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>82<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Microsoft <sup id=3D"cite_ref-83" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite=
_note-83"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> and other design frameworks and tools have also publi=
shed sets of guidelines.
</p><p><br>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Web_accessibility">Web acce=
ssibility</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAc=
cessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: Web =
accessibility"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_accessibility" t=
itle=3D"Web accessibility">Web accessibility</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"International_standards_and=
_guidelines">International standards and guidelines</h4><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: International standards and guideline=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p>There have been a few major movements to coordinate a set of guidelines =
for accessibility for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wi=
de_Web" title=3D"World Wide Web">web</a>. The first and most well known is =
The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Accessibility_Initiative" =
title=3D"Web Accessibility Initiative">Web Accessibility Initiative</a> (WA=
I), which is part of the World Wide Web Consortium (<a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/W3C" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"W3C">W3C</a>). This o=
rganization developed the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Cont=
ent_Accessibility_Guidelines" title=3D"Web Content Accessibility Guidelines=
">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines</a> (WCAG) 1.0 and 2.0 which explain=
 how to make Web content accessible to everyone, including people with disa=
bilities. Web "content" generally refers to the information in a Web page o=
r Web application, including text, images, forms, and sounds. (More specifi=
c definitions are available in the WCAG documents.)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-84" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#=
cite_note-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>84<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The WCAG is separated into three levels of compliance, A, AA and AAA=
. Each level requires a stricter set of conformance guidelines, such as dif=
ferent versions of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML" title=3D"=
HTML">HTML</a> (Transitional vs Strict) and other techniques that need to b=
e incorporated into coding before accomplishing validation. Online tools al=
low users to submit their website and automatically run it through the WCAG=
 guidelines and produce a report, stating whether or not they conform to ea=
ch level of compliance. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adobe_Drea=
mweaver" title=3D"Adobe Dreamweaver">Adobe Dreamweaver</a> also offers plug=
ins which allow web developers to test these guidelines on their work from =
within the program.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO/IEC_JTC_1/SC_36#WG_=
7_Culture.2C_Language.2C_and_Human_Functioning_Activities" title=3D"ISO/IEC=
 JTC 1/SC 36">ISO/IEC JTC1 SC36 WG7</a> 24751 Individualized Adaptability a=
nd Accessibility in e-learning, education and training series is freely ava=
ilable and made of 3 parts: Individualized Adaptability and Accessibility i=
n e-learning, education and training, Standards inventory and Guidance on u=
ser needs mapping.
</p><p>Another source of web accessibility guidance comes from the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_government" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"US government">US government</a>. In response to <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rehabilitation_Act_of_1973#Section_508" title=3D"Rehabi=
litation Act of 1973">Section 508 of the US Rehabilitation Act</a>, the Acc=
ess Board developed standards to which U.S. federal agencies must comply in=
 order to make their sites accessible. The U.S. General Services Administra=
tion has developed a website where one can take online training courses for=
 free to learn about these rules.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-85" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-85"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>85<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Web_accessibility_features"=
>Web accessibility features</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D=
"Edit section: Web accessibility features"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Examples of accessibility features include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Accessibility_Initiati=
ve" title=3D"Web Accessibility Initiative">WAI</a>-AA compliance with the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Content_Accessibility_Guideline=
s" title=3D"Web Content Accessibility Guidelines">WAI's WCAG</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semantic_HTML" title=3D"Semant=
ic HTML">Semantic</a> Web markup</li>
<li>(X)HTML Validation from the W3C for the page's content</li>
<li>CSS Validation from the W3C for the page's layout</li>
<li>Compliance with all guidelines from Section 508 of the US Rehabilitatio=
n Act</li>
<li>A high contrast version of the site for individuals with low vision, an=
d a low contrast (yellow or blue) version of the site for individuals with =
dyslexia</li>
<li>Alternative media for any multimedia used on the site (video, flash, au=
dio, etc.)</li>
<li>Simple and consistent navigation</li>
<li>Device independent</li>
<li>Reducing Cognitive load for decision making</li></ul>
<p>While WCAG provides much technical information for use by web designers,=
 coders and editors, <i>BS 8878:2010 Web accessibility =E2=80=93 Code of Pr=
actice</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-86" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-86"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> has been introd=
uced, initially in the UK, to help site owners and product managers to unde=
rstand the importance of accessibility. It includes advice on the business =
case behind accessibility, and how organisations might usefully update thei=
r policies and production processes to embed accessibility in their busines=
s-as-usual. On 28 May 2019, BS 8878 was superseded by <i>ISO 30071-1</i>,<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-87" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-87"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the international Standard =
that built on BS 8878 and expanded it for international use.
</p><p>Another useful idea is for websites to include a web accessibility s=
tatement on the site. Initially introduced in PAS 78,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-88=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibilit=
y#cite_note-88"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> the best practice for web accessibility stateme=
nts has been updated in BS 8878<sup id=3D"cite_ref-89" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-89"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> to emphasise the inclusion of: information on how disabled and elderl=
y people could get a better experience of using the website by using assist=
ive technologies or accessibility settings of browsers and operating system=
s (linking to "BBC My Web My Way"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-90" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-90"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>90<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> can be useful here); information on what accessibility features the=
 site's creators have included, and if there are any user needs which the s=
ite does not currently support (for example, descriptive video to allow bli=
nd people to access the information in videos more easily); and contact det=
ails for disabled people to be able to use to let the site creators know if=
 they have any problems in using the site. While validations against WCAG, =
and other accessibility badges can also be included, they should be put low=
er down the statement, as most disabled people still do not understand thes=
e technical terms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-91" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-91"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>91<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Education_and_accessibility=
_for_students">Education and accessibility for students</h2><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Education and accessibility for s=
tudents"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Vietnam_phusical_therapy_school_orphanage.jpg=
" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"A woman is helping a young boy =
to stand up in a classroom with other students" src=3D"https://upload.wikim=
edia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Vietnam_phusical_therapy_school_orpha=
nage.jpg/250px-Vietnam_phusical_therapy_school_orphanage.jpg" decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"250" height=3D"367" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-widt=
h=3D"697" data-file-height=3D"1024"></a><figcaption>A teacher helps her stu=
dent in an orphanage in central <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vi=
etnam" title=3D"Vietnam">Vietnam</a>. The orphanage caters to many abandone=
d and disabled children who, through education and communication programs, =
are able to have a life that would otherwise not be possible.</figcaption><=
/figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Latrine_ramp_school.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-des=
cription"><img alt=3D"People constructing a ramp for an accessible bathroom=
" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Latrine_=
ramp_school.jpg/250px-Latrine_ramp_school.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"=
250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3648" data=
-file-height=3D"2736"></a><figcaption>Construction of a ramp for a school l=
atrine in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ukunda" title=3D"Ukunda"=
>Ukunda</a>, Kenya, to make the school building more accessible to students=
 with disabilities</figcaption></figure>
<p>Equal access to education for students with disabilities is supported in=
 some countries by legislation. It is still challenging for some students w=
ith disabilities to fully participate in mainstream education settings, but=
 many adaptive technologies and assistive programs are making improvements.=
 In India, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_Council_of_=
India" title=3D"Medical Council of India">Medical Council of India</a> has =
now passed the directives to all the medical institutions to make them acce=
ssible to persons with disabilities. This happened due to a petition by Sat=
endra Singh founder of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_Ab=
ility" title=3D"Infinite Ability">Infinite Ability</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
92" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibil=
ity#cite_note-92"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>92<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Students with a physical or mental impairment or learning disability=
 may require note-taking assistance, which may be provided by a business of=
fering such services, as with tutoring services. Talking books in the form =
of talking textbooks are available in Canadian secondary and post-secondary=
 schools. Also, students may require adaptive technology to access computer=
s and the Internet. These may be tax-exempt expenses in some jurisdictions =
with a medical prescription.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Accessibility_of_assessment=
s">Accessibility of assessments</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DAccessibility&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=
=3D"Edit section: Accessibility of assessments"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>It is important to ensure that the accessibility in education includes a=
ssessments.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-93" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>93<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Accessibility =
in testing or assessments entails the extent to which a test and its consti=
tuent item set eliminates barriers and permits the test-taker to demonstrat=
e their knowledge of the tested content.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-94" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-9=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>94<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>With the passage of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No_=
Child_Left_Behind_Act" title=3D"No Child Left Behind Act">No Child Left Beh=
ind Act</a> of 2001 in the United States,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-95" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-=
95"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>95<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> student accountability in essential content areas such as r=
eading, mathematics, and science has become a major area of focus in educat=
ional reform.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-96" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-96"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As a result,=
 test developers have needed to create tests to ensure all students, includ=
ing those with special needs (e.g., students identified with disabilities),=
 are given the opportunity to demonstrate the extent to which they have mas=
tered the content measured on state assessments. Currently, states are perm=
itted to develop two different types of tests in addition to the standard g=
rade-level assessments to target students with special needs. First, the al=
ternate assessment may be used to report proficiency for up to 1% of studen=
ts in a state. Second, new regulations permit the use of alternate assessme=
nts based on modified academic achievement standards to report proficiency =
for up to 2% of students in a state.
</p><p>To ensure that these new tests generate results that allow valid inf=
erences to be made about student performance, they must be accessible to as=
 many people as possible. The Test Accessibility and Modification Inventory=
 (TAMI)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-97" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility#cite_note-97"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>97<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and its companion =
evaluation tool, the Accessibility Rating Matrix (ARM), were designed to fa=
cilitate the evaluation of tests and test items with a focus on enhancing t=
heir accessibility. Both instruments incorporate the principles of accessib=
ility theory and were guided by research on universal design, assessment ac=
cessibility, cognitive load theory, and research on item writing and test d=
evelopment. The TAMI is a non-commercial instrument that has been made avai=
lable to all state assessment directors and testing companies. Assessment r=
esearchers have used the ARM to conduct accessibility reviews of state asse=
ssment items for several state departments of education.
</p>
